\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Logical consequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are given propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1},\ldots,C_{m}$
\end_inset

, composed of propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},\ldots,A_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Let us determine all propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}\sledi B
\]

\end_inset

is a tautology.
 Such a proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is called 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 logical consequence
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1},\ldots,C_{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Special cases: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}$
\end_inset

 tautology 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi B$
\end_inset

 tautology 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}$
\end_inset

 contradiction 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi B$
\end_inset

 any proposition 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Otherwise, we take the following approach:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We express the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}$
\end_inset

 in its canonical CNF.
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}$
\end_inset

 is the conjunction of a number of basic disjunctions (maxterms), composed
 of propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},\ldots,A_{n}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\ali\ali\ali)\inn(\ali\ali\ali)\inn\cdots\inn(\ali\ali\ali)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following holds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the conjunction of any number of these maxterms, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}\sledi B
\]

\end_inset

is a tautology!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Indeed: if proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}$
\end_inset

 is true, then all the maxterms appearing in the canonical CNF of it are
 true.
 Therefore also the conjunction of any number of these maxterms is true.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}\sledi B$
\end_inset

 is a tautology, then the canonical CNF of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 can only contain those maxterms that also appear in the canonical CNF of
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Indeed: if, in the canonical CNF of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 we have a maxterm corresponding to a truth assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, which does not appear in the canonical CNF for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}$
\end_inset

, then proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is false at 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, while proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}$
\end_inset

 is true at 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 This is a contradiction with the assumption that 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn\cdots\inn C_{m}\sledi B$
\end_inset

 is a tautology.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

: A man speaks the truth or is not brave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

: If a man is free, he is brave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

: A man speaks the truth.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

: A man is brave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}$
\end_inset

: A man is free.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}:A_{1}\ali\neg A_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}:A_{3}\sledi A_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn C_{2}:(A_{1}\ali\neg A_{2})\inn(A_{3}\sledi A_{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 Truth table:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{tabular}{c|c|c|c|c|c|c}
\hline  %after
 &  \ensuremath{A_{1}}  &  \ensuremath{A_{2}}  &  \ensuremath{A_{3}}  &  \ensuremath{A_{1}\ali\neg A_{2}}  &  \ensuremath{A_{3}\sledi A_{2}}  &  \ensuremath{C_{1}\inn C_{2}} \\
\hline  1.  &  1  &  1  &  1  &  1  &  1  &  1 \\
 2.  &  1  &  1  &  0  &  1  &  1  &  1 \\
 3.  &  1  &  0  &  1  &  1  &  0  &  0 \\
 4.  &  1  &  0  &  0  &  1  &  1  &  1 \\
 5.  &  0  &  1  &  1  &  0  &  1  &  0 \\
 6.  &  0  &  1  &  0  &  0  &  1  &  0 \\
 7.  &  0  &  0  &  1  &  1  &  0  &  0 \\
 8.  &  0  &  0  &  0  &  1  &  1  &  1 \\
  &   &   &   &   &  
\end{tabular}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Canonical CNF: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\neg A_{1}\ali A_{2}\ali\neg A_{3})\inn(A_{1}\ali\neg A_{2}\ali\neg A_{3})\inn(A_{1}\ali\neg A_{2}\ali A_{3})\inn(A_{1}\ali A_{2}\ali\neg A_{3})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can obtain all logical consequences that are not tautologies by choosing
 one or more maxterms and connecting them conjunctively.
 The number of such consequences is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{4 \choose 1}+{4 \choose 2}+{4 \choose 3}+{4 \choose 4}=4+6+4+1=15\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us analyze one of them: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A_{1}\ali\neg A_{2}\ali\neg A_{3})\inn(A_{1}\ali A_{2}\ali\neg A_{3})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A_{1}\ali\neg A_{3}\ali\neg A_{2})\inn(A_{1}\ali\neg A_{3}\ali A_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
((A_{1}\ali\neg A_{3})\ali\neg A_{2})\inn((A_{1}\ali\neg A_{3})\ali A_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A_{1}\ali\neg A_{3})\ali(\neg A_{2}\inn A_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{1}\ali\neg A_{3}
\]

\end_inset

The proposition reads: 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A man speaks the truth or is not free.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose also that somebody asks us: Is proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 a tautological consequence of propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, we express proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 in its canonical CNF with respect to the atomic propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applying implication (18) twice, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{1}\ali(A_{2}\inn\neg A_{2})\ali(A_{3}\inn\neg A_{3})\,.
\]

\end_inset

Applying distributivity, we obtain the canonical CNF of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A_{1}\ali A_{2}\ali A_{3})\inn(A_{1}\ali A_{2}\ali\neg A_{3})\inn(A_{1}\ali\neg A_{2}\ali A_{3})\inn(A_{1}\ali\neg A_{2}\ali\neg A_{3})\,.
\]

\end_inset

We notice that disjunction 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\ali A_{2}\ali A_{3}$
\end_inset

 does not appear in the canonical CNF of proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn C_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the answer to the above question is: no.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% 7.
 predavanje, 60', 25.
 10.
 2012
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Inference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Facts: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
I will go to the match.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the evening, I will do the homework.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If I go to the match and then to the cinema, I will not have the time to
 do the homework.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can I infer that I will not be able to go to the cinema?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us define the following propositions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

: I will go to the match.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

: In the evening, I will do the homework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}$
\end_inset

: I will go to the cinema.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\inn A_{3}\sledi\neg A_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have to determine whether the implication 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{1}\inn C_{2}\inn C_{3}\sledi\neg A_{3}
\]

\end_inset

is a tautology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose this is not the case: let 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 be a truth assignment for whoch the antecedent 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn C_{2}\inn C_{3}$
\end_inset

 is true, while the consequent 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg A_{3}$
\end_inset

 is false.
 Since the consequent 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg A_{3}(d)$
\end_inset

 is false, the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}(d)$
\end_inset

 is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the antecedent 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn C_{2}\inn C_{3}$
\end_inset

 is true, both propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}=A_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}=A_{2}$
\end_inset

 are true for assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 What is the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}$
\end_inset

, that is,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\inn A_{3}\sledi\neg A_{2}$
\end_inset

? Proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\inn A_{3}$
\end_inset

 is true at assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, while proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg A_{2}$
\end_inset

 is false.
 Therefore, also proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{3}$
\end_inset

 is false.
 However this is a contradiction with the assumption that the conjunction
 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn C_{2}\inn C_{3}$
\end_inset

 (antecedent) is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This contradiction shows that the implication 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{1}\inn C_{2}\inn C_{3}\sledi\neg A_{3}
\]

\end_inset

is indeed a tautology, hence the above inference is correct.
 (I will not make it to the cinema.) 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following facts are given: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This bird is not a bird, or it has wings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If this animal is a bird, then it lays eggs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is the following inference correct? 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If this animal does not have wings, then it does not lay eggs.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us define the following propositions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

: This animal is a bird.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

: This animal has wings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}$
\end_inset

: This animal lays eggs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg A_{1}\ali A_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\sledi A_{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg A_{2}\sledi\neg A_{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have to determine whether the implication 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{1}\inn C_{2}\sledi B
\]

\end_inset

is a tautology.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So let us suppose that it is not: let 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 be a truth assignment at which the antecedens 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn C_{2}$
\end_inset

 is true and the consequent 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is false.
 Since the consequent 
\begin_inset Formula $B(d)$
\end_inset

 is false, the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg A_{2}(d)$
\end_inset

 is true, and the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg A_{3}(d)$
\end_inset

 is false.
 It follows that the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}(d)$
\end_inset

 is false, and the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}(d)$
\end_inset

 is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since the antecedens 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\inn C_{2}$
\end_inset

 is true at the truth assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, also the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 is true at 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg A_{1}\ali A_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 However since the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}(d)$
\end_inset

 is false, the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg A_{1}(d)$
\end_inset

 must be correct.
 Equivalently: proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

 is false at truth assignemnt 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The truth assignment is already completely determined with this: 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}(d)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}(d)$
\end_inset

 are false propositions, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}(d)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 We can check that also the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 is correct at this truth assignment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have not reached a contradiction, we constructed a truth assignment,
 for which the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{1}\inn C_{2}\sledi B
\]

\end_inset

is flase.
 (This happens only in the case when 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 this animal is not a bird, it has no wings, and lays eggs.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{sloppypar}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The above examples nicely illustrate that the process of proving that a
 particular proposition is a tautology is the same as the process of proving
 that the a certain proposition is not a tautology.
 In both cases, we are trying to construct a truth assignment 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, for which the proposition is false.
 If we do that, then we have a proof that the proposition is not a tautology.
 If we get a contradiction, we have thus proved that the proposition is
 a tautology!
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{sloppypar}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Homework:
\series default
 Found out whether the following inference is correct.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Facts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Duke was killed by one of his staff: the cook, the servant or the driver.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the killer was the cook, she poisoned the food.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the killer was the driver, he put a bomb in the car.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The food was not poisoned and the servant is not a murderer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conclusion: The killer was the driver.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Propositions with quantifiers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantifiers tell, for how many objects of some kind a given proposition
 is true.
 We will use the following notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$
\backslash
forall$...
 za vsak
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$
\backslash
exists$ ...
 obstaja (s tujko: eksistira)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$
\backslash
exists!$ ...
 obstaja natanko eden.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)A(x)$
\end_inset

 ...
 for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A(x)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x)A(x)$
\end_inset

 ...
 there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A(x)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists!x)A(x)$
\end_inset

 ...
 there exists a unique (that is, one and only one) 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $A(x)$
\end_inset

 is true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Examples:
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall$
\end_inset

 natural numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $n)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists n)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is a natural number and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is divisible by 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists!n)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the smallest natural number).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Negation of propositions with quantifiers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Negation 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall$
\end_inset


\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(\forall x)A(x)\cee(\exists x)(\neg A(x))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

: Every citizen of Slovenia is dark haired.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\neg B$
\end_inset

: It is not true that every citizen of Slovenia is dark haired.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalently: There exists at least one citizen of Slovenia that is not
 dark haired.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\series bold
Negation 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists$
\end_inset


\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(\exists x)A(x)\cee(\forall x)\neg A(x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

: There is a red ball in the box.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\neg B$
\end_inset

: It is not true that there is a red ball in the box.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalently: For every ball in the box, it holds that it is not red.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent

\series bold
Negation 
\begin_inset Formula $\exists!$
\end_inset


\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(\exists!x)A(x)\cee(\forall x)(\neg A(x))\ali(\exists x)(\exists y)(x\neq y\inn A(x)\inn A(y))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

: There exists a unique prime number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\neg B$
\end_inset

: It is not true that there exists a unique prime number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalently: Either no number is prime, or there exists at least two different
 prime numbers.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is the following proposition correct?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There exists a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{1+x^{2}}>1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists x)(\frac{1}{1+x^{2}}>1)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No, the proposition is not true.
 We can check that its negation is true: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(\exists x)(\frac{1}{1+x^{2}}>1)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee(\forall x)\neg(\frac{1}{1+x^{2}}>1)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee(\forall x)(\frac{1}{1+x^{2}}\le1)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee(\forall x)(1\le1+x^{2})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee(\forall x)(0\le x^{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg\left(\exists\textrm{ realno tevilo }x:\frac{1}{x^{2}+1}>1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x)$
\end_inset

 denote the proposition 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is prime
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
For every natural number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 there exists a natural number 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, bigger than 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, that is a prime number: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(\exists y)(y>x\inn P(y))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Negation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(\forall x)(\exists y)(y>x\inn P(y))\cee(\exists x)\neg(\exists y)(y>x\inn P(y))
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee(\exists x)(\forall y)\neg(y>x\inn P(y))\cee(\exists x)(\forall y)(y\le x\ali\neg P(y))\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us write the negation of the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall x)(\exists y)(y<x)\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(\forall x)(\exists y)(y<x)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists x)(\neg(\exists y)(y<x))
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists x)(\forall y)\neg(y<x)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists x)(\forall y)(y\ge x)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is the following proposition true in real numbers? 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall x)(\exists y)(y<x)
\]

\end_inset

Yes, the proposition is true! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is it true in natural numbers? 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall x)(\exists y)(y<x)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
No, its negation is true: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists x)(\forall y)(y\ge x)\,,
\]

\end_inset

since there exists a smallest natural number.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Set Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Elements (objects): 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,\ldots,x,y,z$
\end_inset

 (+ indices: 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{6},x_{1},z_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sets: 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B,\ldots,X,Y,Z$
\end_inset

 (+ indices)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a\in F$
\end_inset

: element 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 belongs to set 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is an element of set 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\in$
\end_inset

: symbol of containment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a\not\in F$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is not an element of (does not belong to) set 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is the set of all even numbers, then 
\begin_inset Formula $16\in G$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $3\not\in G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Equality of sets:
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are equal if and only if they have exactly the same objects as elements:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=B\cee(\forall x)(x\in A\cee x\in B)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 This definition is necessary, since it describes an important property
 that the containment relation must satisfy!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 Suppose that the objects under consideration are people, and let us write
 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an ancestor of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Can we use this definition to define people as sets? The above equivalence
 says: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If two people are the same then they have the same ancestors.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This is true.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If two people have the same ancestors, then they are the same.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This however is not true! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 A set can be given by a list of all its elements: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\left\{ 1,\frac{1}{2},\frac{\pi}{3},2i+8\right\} \,.
\]

\end_inset

The order 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is irrelevant!
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 Sometimes such a description is impractical: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the set is infinite (e.g., the set of all prime numbers).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the set is finite but too large (e.g., the set of all books that were printed
 on Planet Earth until the year 2011), 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 A set can also be given by a description of it.
 The description must be unambiguous: for every object, it must hold that
 it either belongs to the set, or that it does not belong to the set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be the set of all complex numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 that are a solution of some equation of the form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}x^{n}+a_{n-1}x^{n-1}+\cdots+a_{1}x+a_{0}=0\,,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,1,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 - the set of all algebraic numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{\pi}\in A$
\end_inset

? We do not know (contemporary mathematics cannot yet give an answer this
 question).
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 In general, we can write: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{x;P(x)\}\,,
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the set of all elements 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x)$
\end_inset

 is true.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Or, if we have several propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{1},\ldots,P_{n}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{x;P_{1}(x)\inn\cdots\inn P_{n}(x)\}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\{x;P_{1}(x)\ali\cdots\ali P_{n}(x)\}
\]

\end_inset

As we will see soon, we can build such sets only with elements of the sets
 that we already know (or for which we know that they exist).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 be the set of all people.
 Propositions `
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is married
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is at least 20 years old
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

are meaningful for elements of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we can construct sets 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{x\in L;x\textrm{ is married}\}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{x\in L;x\textrm{ is married}\inn x\textrm{ is at least 20 years old}\}
\]

\end_inset

as well as (by negating the above conjunction) 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{x\in L;x\textrm{ is not married}\ali x\textrm{ is not at least 20 years old}\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{x\in L;x\textrm{ is the current president of Republic of Slovenia}\}
\]

\end_inset

contains only Borut Pahor and nothing else.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 Be careful: a box that contains a hat is not the same thing as the hat.
 Similarly, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a\}$
\end_inset

 is not the same thing as 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 For every object 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\{a\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Subsets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are given two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 subset
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 if and only if every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is also an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notation: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\subseteq B\cee(\forall x)(x\in A\sledi x\in B)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, every set is a subset of itself: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall A)(A\subseteq A)\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\neq B$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 proper subset 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\subset B\cee(A\subseteq B\inn A\neq B)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, it holds that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\inn B\subseteq A\cee A=B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
This equivalence is extremely important for proving equality of two sets!
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\inn B\subseteq C\sledi A\subseteq C\textrm{~(transitivity of inclusion)}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For our proof of equivalence 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\inn B\subseteq A\cee A=B$
\end_inset

, we will need the following equivalence: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall x)(P(x)\inn Q(x))\cee(\forall x)P(x)\inn(\forall x)Q(x)\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\Rightarrow)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof by contradiction.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(P(x)\inn Q(x))$
\end_inset

, while
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\neg((\forall x)P(x)\inn(\forall x)Q(x))\,.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then: 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg(\forall x)P(x)\ali\neg(\forall x)Q(x)\,.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x)\neg P(x)\ali(\exists x)\neg Q(x)\,.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Independently of which of the propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x)\neg P(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x)\neg Q(x)$
\end_inset

 is true, we have a contradiction with proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(P(x)\inn Q(x))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\Leftarrow)$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof by contradiction.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)P(x)\inn(\forall x)Q(x)\,,$
\end_inset

 while
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\neg(\forall x)(P(x)\inn Q(x))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x)\neg(P(x)\inn Q(x))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists x)(\neg P(x)\ali\neg Q(x))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg P(x)\ali\neg Q(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Independently of which of the propositions 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg P(x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg Q(x)$
\end_inset

 is true, we have a contradiction with proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)P(x)\inn(\forall x)Q(x)\,.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Let us now prove the equivalence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\subseteq B\inn B\subseteq A\cee A=B\,:
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\subseteq B\inn B\subseteq A
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall x)(x\in A\sledi x\in B)\inn(\forall x)(x\in B\sledi x\in A)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall x)((x\in A\sledi x\in B)\inn(x\in B\sledi x\in A))
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall x)(x\in A\cee x\in B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=B\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Homework:
\series default
 prove the above implication (transitivity of inclusion).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
A question:
\series default
 Do there exist two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subset A$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Be careful:
\series default
 relation of inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

 and relation of containment 
\begin_inset Formula $\in$
\end_inset

 are two completely different notions!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $1\in\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is not a subset of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

.
 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1\}$
\end_inset

 is a subset of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1\}$
\end_inset

 is not an element of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Some questions:
\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X=\{1,2,\{1\},\{2\}\}$
\end_inset

.
 Is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

? Is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

? Is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1\}$
\end_inset

 an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

? Is 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1\}$
\end_inset

 a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Empty set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote the set that has no elements with symbol 
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 — 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 empty set
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X=\emptyset\cee(\forall x)(x\not\in X)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course it holds that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall X)(\emptyset\subseteq X)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
A short discussion about axioms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every mathematical theory is based on a set of axioms — basic propositions
 that we 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

em assume
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to be correct.
 These axioms define the basic properties that objects of a certain theory
 should satisfy (e.g.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

integers, real numbers, groups, vector spaces, graphs, manifolds, ...).
 From the axioms new truths (claims, consequences, theorems ...) are derived
 by logical reasoning.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Set Theory, the situation is the same! There are several families of
 axioms, but the most established are seven particular axioms, called 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

em axioms of ZFC
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (Zermelo - Fraenkel - (Axiom of) Choice).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These axioms ensure the existence of sets and ways of forming new sets from
 existing ones.
 Except for the Axiom of Choice, which is of special interest, we will not
 discuss other axioms here in detail.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand why we need the axioms, let's see why the set of all sets
 does not exist!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Russell's Antinomy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can form sets of sets (or families of sets).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}$
\end_inset

: The set of rational numbers is a set of sets: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0,5=\left\{ \frac{1}{2},\frac{2}{4},\frac{3}{6},\cdots\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

(Fraction is understood as an ordered pair of integers.
 Ordered pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 can be defined as the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\{a\},\{a,b\}\}$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

medskip Is there a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 set of all sets?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose there is.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be the set of all sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each set, we can ask whether it contains itself as an element.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is not an element of itself! The set of all abstract notions has itself
 as an element.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 be that subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that has for elements precisely those sets from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that do not contain themselves as elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Does the set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 contain itself as an element?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If yes, then it does not contain itself as an element!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What if 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 does not contain itself as an element? Then, by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $B\in B$
\end_inset

, a contradiction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The set of all sets does not exist!
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centerline{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Nothing contains everything.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textit{(mathematical) space does not exist.}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So, in forming new sets we should not trust too much our intuition ...
 Axioms are needed to ensure the existence of certain sets (e.g.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

the axiom of pairs, the axiom of subsets).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Ordered pair
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider two objects 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a\neq b$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a,b\}$
\end_inset

 the order is irrelevant, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a,b\}=\{b,a\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the order of elements is important, we speak about an 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ordered pair
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 - ordered pair, 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)\neq(b,a)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 - first coordinate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 - second coordinate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When are two ordered pairs the same? 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(a,b)=(u,v)\cee a=u\inn b=v\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Remark:
\series default
 Ordered pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(a,b)$
\end_inset

 can also be defined as the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\{a\},\{a,b\}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Homework:
\series default
 Prove that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{\{a\},\{a,b\}\}=\{\{u\},\{u,v\}\}\cee a=u\inn b=v\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Union
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are given two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 union
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of these two sets is the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup B$
\end_inset

, that has for elements precisely those objects that are elements of the
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 or of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\cup B=\{x;x\in A\ali x\in B\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,3,5,7\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{1,2,4,8\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup B=\{1,3,5,7,2,4,8\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Union of several sets
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}=\{A_{\lambda};\lambda\in J\}$
\end_inset

 - union of sets with index set 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The index set can be an arbitrary set!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We define the union of an arbitrary family of sets as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cup{\cal A}=\cup_{\lambda\in J}A_{\lambda}=\{x;(\exists\lambda)(\lambda\in J\inn x\in A_{\lambda})\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\{1,2\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cup_{\lambda\in\{1,2\}}A_{\lambda}=\{x;(\exists\lambda)(\lambda\in\{1,2\}\inn x\in A_{\lambda})\}=\{x;x\in A_{1}\ali x\in A_{2}\}=A_{1}\cup A_{2}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is finite, we usually take 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\{1,2,\ldots,n\}$
\end_inset

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cup{\cal A}=\cup_{j=1}^{n}A_{j}=A_{1}\cup\cdots\cup A_{n}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Basic properties of the union:
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup B=B\cup A$
\end_inset

, commutativity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(A\cup B)\cup C=A\cup(B\cup C)$
\end_inset

, associativity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup A=A$
\end_inset

, idempotency 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup\emptyset=A$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq A\cup B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq A\cup B$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\cee A\cup B=B$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq C\inn B\subseteq C\sledi A\cup B\subseteq C$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Let us prove the property 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\subseteq B\cee A\cup B=B\,:
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 We will show the equivalence by proving the converse equivalence 
\begin_inset Formula $\neg(A\subseteq B)\cee\neg(A\cup B=B)\,:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(A\subseteq B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(\forall x)(x\in A\sledi x\in B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists x)(x\in A\inn x\not\in B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists x)((x\in A\inn x\not\in B)\ali(x\in B\inn x\not\in B))
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists x)((x\in A\ali x\in B)\inn x\not\in B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists x)(x\in A\cup B\inn x\not\in B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(A\cup B\subseteq B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(A\cup B\subseteq B)\ali\neg(B\subseteq A\cup B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg((A\cup B\subseteq B)\inn(B\subseteq A\cup B))
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\neg(A\cup B=B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Homework:
\series default
 Prove the remaining properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
subsection*{Ponovitev:}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Zadnjiè smo zaèeli z obravnavo mnoic.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Relaciji pripadnosti $
\backslash
in$ and inkluzije $
\backslash
subseteq$.
 Podmnoica, prazna set, Russellova antinomija, urejeni par, unija.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
medskip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


