\begin_layout Subsection*
Intersection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are given two sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 intersection
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of these two sets is the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B$
\end_inset

, that contains as elements precisely those objects that are elements of
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and of set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\cap B=\{x;x\in A\inn x\in B\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,3,5,7\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{1,2,4,8\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\{1\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Intersection of several sets
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}=\{A_{\lambda};\lambda\in J\}$
\end_inset

 - a family of sets with index set 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $J\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The index set is an arbitrary nonempty set!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can define the intersection of an arbitrary nonempty family of sets as
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cap{\cal A}=\cap_{\lambda\in J}A_{\lambda}=\{x;(\forall\lambda)(\lambda\in J\sledi x\in A_{\lambda})\}
\]

\end_inset

(If 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, we would have 
\begin_inset Formula $\cap{\cal A}$
\end_inset

 = everything.
 But such a set does not exist.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

 is finite, we usually take 
\begin_inset Formula $J=\{1,2,\ldots,n\}$
\end_inset

 and write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cap{\cal A}=\cap_{j=1}^{n}A_{j}=A_{1}\cap\cdots\cap A_{n}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, we say that the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 disjoint
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Basic properties of intersection:
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B=B\cap A$
\end_inset

, commutativity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(A\cap B)\cap C=A\cap(B\cap C)$
\end_inset

, associativity 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap A=A$
\end_inset

, idempotency 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap\emptyset=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B\subseteq A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B\subseteq B$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\cee A\cap B=A$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\inn A\subseteq C\sledi A\subseteq B\cap C$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Homework:
\series default
 Prove the above properties.
 (Proofs are similar to the proofs of analogous properties of the union.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 The union and the intersection are related via the distributivity laws:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A\cup B)\cap C=(A\cap C)\cup(B\cap C)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A\cap B)\cup C=(A\cup C)\cap(B\cup C)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us prove the first distributivity law: 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\cup B)\cap C=(A\cap C)\cup(B\cap C)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 How do we show equality of two sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $X=Y$
\end_inset

? There are several possibilities: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We show the correctness of the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(x\in X\cee x\in Y)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
OR: 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
We show 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq Y$
\end_inset

, that is, the correctness of the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(x\in X\sledi x\in Y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
We also show 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, that is, the correctness of the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(x\in Y\sledi x\in X)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let's have a look at the first approach: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in(A\cup B)\cap C
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\in A\cup B)\inn(x\in C)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\in A\ali x\in B)\inn(x\in C)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\in A\inn x\in C)\ali(x\in B\inn x\in C)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\in A\cap C)\ali(x\in B\cap C)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in(A\cap C)\cup(B\cap C)\,.
\]

\end_inset

Since the above chain of equivalences holds for an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the proposition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall x)(x\in(A\cup B)\cap C\cee x\in(A\cap C)\cup(B\cap C))
\]

\end_inset

is correct.
 Hence, the sets are equal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The distributivity laws also hold more generally, for nonempty set families:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\bigcup_{\lambda\in J}A_{\lambda})\cap(\bigcup_{\mu\in K}B_{\mu})=\bigcup_{\lambda\in J,\mu\in K}(A_{\lambda}\cap B_{\mu})\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\bigcap_{\lambda\in J}A_{\lambda})\cup(\bigcap_{\mu\in K}B_{\mu})=\bigcap_{\lambda\in J,\mu\in K}(A_{\lambda}\cup B_{\mu})\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Homework:
\series default
 Prove that for arbitrary three sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 it holds that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A\cap B)\cup C=A\cap(B\cup C)\cee C\subseteq A\,.
\]

\end_inset

(The condition on the right does not depend on 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

!)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Homework solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us prove transitivity of inclusion: 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\inn B\subseteq C\sledi A\subseteq C$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Direct proof:
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq C$
\end_inset

.
 We need to show: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(x\in A\sledi x\in C)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B$
\end_inset

, it follows 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subseteq C$
\end_inset

, it follows 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in C$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 was arbitrary, we proved 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(x\in A\sledi x\in C)$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Set difference
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are given two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 difference
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the set that contains as elements precisely those objects that are elements
 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 but they are not elements of set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\brez B=\{x;x\in A\inn x\not\in B\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be the set of all prime numbers, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 the set of all positive odd numbers.
 Then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A\brez B=\{2\}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 is the only even prime)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $B\brez A=\{1,9,15,21,25,\ldots\}$
\end_inset

 (the set of all odd numbers that are not primes)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Basic properties: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\brez A=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\brez(A\cap B)=A\brez B$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap(A\brez B)=A\brez B$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\brez(B\cup C)=(A\brez B)\cap(A\brez C)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\brez(B\cap C)=(A\brez B)\cup(A\brez C)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(A\brez B)\cup B=A\cup B$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(A\cup B)\brez B=A\brez B$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(A\cap B)\brez B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(A\brez B)\cap B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us prove the equality 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\brez B)\cup B=A\cup B$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in(A\brez B)\cup B
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in A\brez B\ali x\in B
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\in A\inn x\not\in B)\ali x\in B
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\in A\ali x\in B)\inn(x\not\in B\ali x\in B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x\in A\ali x\in B)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in A\cup B
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Homework:
\series default
 Prove the remaining properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
