\begin_layout Subsection*
Complement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Very frequently in mathemathics, we are in the following situation: we are
 given some 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 universal set
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, and only care about the elements and subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq S$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can define the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 complement of set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 (relative to 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C_{S}A=\overline{A}=S\brez A\,.
\]

\end_inset

If the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is not defined, we cannot talk about the complemet: 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\emptyset}$
\end_inset

 = set of all sets — which does not exist (Russell's antinomy)!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{0,1,2,3,\ldots\}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all natural numbers, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be the set of all prime numbers.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A}=\{0,1,4,6,8,9,10,12,\ldots\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 Properties of the complement: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{S}=\emptyset,~~~~\overline{\emptyset}=S$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\overline{A}}=A,~~~A\cup\overline{A}=S,~~~~A\cap\overline{A}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\brez B=A\cap\overline{B}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\cee\overline{B}\subseteq\overline{A}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A=B\cee\overline{A}=\overline{B}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A\cup B}=\overline{A}\cap\overline{B}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\overline{A\cap B}=\overline{A}\cup\overline{B}$
\end_inset

 (De Morgan's laws) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
De Morgan's laws also hold for an arbitrary family of sets 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}=\{A_{\lambda}~;~\lambda\in J\}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\cup_{\lambda\in J}A_{\lambda}}={\cap_{\lambda\in J}\overline{A}_{\lambda}}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\cap_{\lambda\in J}A_{\lambda}}={\cup_{\lambda\in J}\overline{A}_{\lambda}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of De Morgan's laws, theorems about sets often come in pairs.
 If in a given inclusion, equality or equivalence about unions, intersections
 and complements of subsets of a certain set we replace each set with its
 complement, we interchange all union and intersections, and reverse all
 inclusions, the result is again a valid inclusion, equality or equivalence.
 This principle is called 
\series bold
principle of duality
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposition 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A\cap B)\cup C=A\cap(B\cup C)\cee C\subseteq A\,.
\]

\end_inset

becomes 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\overline{A}\cup\overline{B})\cap\overline{C}=\overline{A}\cup(\overline{B}\cap\overline{C})\cee\overline{A}\subseteq\overline{C}\,,
\]

\end_inset

which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A\cup B)\cap C=A\cup(B\cap C)\cee A\subseteq C
\]

\end_inset

(after interchanging the roles of sets and their complements).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

