\begin_layout Subsection*
Power set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 power set
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of a given set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the family of sets that contains as elements precisely all the subsets
 of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal P}(A)=\{X;X\subseteq A\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(\{1,2\})=\{\emptyset,\{1\},\{2\},\{1,2\}\}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(\emptyset)=\{\emptyset\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(\{\emptyset\})=\{\emptyset,\{\emptyset\}\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements, then its power set 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(A)$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 elementov.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 we need to decide, independently of the other elements, whether to include
 it in 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq A$
\end_inset

 or not.
 Thus, altogether we have 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 independent choices of one out of two possibilities, which, for all subsets
 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq A$
\end_inset

, gives us exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{n}$
\end_inset

 possobilities.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Properties: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq B\sledi\P(A)\subseteq\P(B)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\P(A)\cup\P(B)\subseteq\P(A\cup B)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\P(A)\cap\P(B)=\P(A\cap B)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first property follows from transitivity of inclusion:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\P(A)\inn A\subseteq B\cee X\subseteq A\subseteq B\sledi X\subseteq B\cee X\in\P(B)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof of the second property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\P(A)\cup\P(B)\cee X\subseteq A\ali X\subseteq B\sledi X\subseteq A\cup B\cee X\in\P(A\cup B)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof of the third property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\P(A)\cap\P(B)\cee X\in\P(A)\inn A\in\P(B)\cee X\subseteq A\inn X\subseteq B$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\cee X\subseteq A\cap B\cee X\in\P(A\cap B)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%{
\backslash
bf V razmislek:} Zakaj velja predzadnja equivalence v zgornji verigi ekvivalenc?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
medskip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%{
\backslash
bf Homework:} Formalno dokaite prvo and drugo lastnost.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
A question:
\series default
 Why in the second property we don't have equality?
\end_layout

