\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Solution of one of the homeworks:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us show that for every three subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, it holds that: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(A\cap B)\cup C=A\cap(B\cup C)\cee C\subseteq A\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Rightarrow)$
\end_inset

: Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\cap B)\cup C=A\cap(B\cup C)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq(A\cap B)\cup C=A\cap(B\cup C)\subseteq A$
\end_inset

.
 We use transitivity of inclusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\Leftarrow)$
\end_inset

: Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $C\subseteq A$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cup C=A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $(A\cap B)\cup C=(A\cup C)\cap(B\cup C)=A\cap(B\cup C)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us prove one of De Morgan's laws for an arbitrary set family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}=\{A_{\lambda}~;~\lambda\in J\}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\cup_{\lambda\in J}A_{\lambda}}={\cap_{\lambda\in J}\overline{A}_{\lambda}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in\overline{\cup_{\lambda\in J}A_{\lambda}}\cee x\not\in\cup_{\lambda\in J}A_{\lambda}\cee\neg(\exists\lambda)(\lambda\in J\inn x\in A_{\lambda})\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee(\forall\lambda)(\lambda\in J\sledi\neg(x\in A_{\lambda}))\cee(\forall\lambda)(\lambda\in J\sledi x\in\overline{A_{\lambda}})\cee x\in{\cap_{\lambda\in J}\overline{A}_{\lambda}}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Cartesian product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Cartesian product
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the set that contains as elements precisely all the ordered pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)$
\end_inset

 such that the first coordinate is from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and the second coordinate is from 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\times B=\{(x,y)~;~x\in A\inn y\in B\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1\}\times\{2,3\}=\{(1,2),(1,3)\}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\{2,3\}\times\{1\}=\{(2,1),(3,1)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Properties of the Cartesian product: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B\neq B\times A$
\end_inset

 (unless 
\begin_inset Formula $A=B$
\end_inset

) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\times B=\emptyset\cee A=\emptyset\ali B=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\times(B\cup C)=(A\times B)\cup(A\times C)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\times(B\cap C)=(A\times B)\cap(A\times C)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A\times(B\brez C)=(A\times B)\brez(A\times C)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Cartesian product of three sets can be defined as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\times B\times C=(A\times B)\times C=\{((x,y),z)~;~x\in A\inn y\in B\inn z\in C\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Usually, we write just: 
\begin_inset Formula $((x,y),z)=(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

 (ordered triple).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 The Cartesian product of sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},\ldots,A_{n}$
\end_inset

 is defined as the set of all ordered 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-tuples: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{1}\times A_{2}\times\cdots\times A_{n}=\prod_{i=1}^{n}A_{i}=\{(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n})~;~x_{1}\in A_{1}\inn x_{2}\in A_{2}\inn\cdots\inn x_{n}\in A_{n}\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Within every mathematical theory 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal T}$
\end_inset

 with universal set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 we can represent every meaningful property 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x)$
\end_inset

 with the set 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\{x~;~x\in S\inn P(x)\}\,.
\]

\end_inset

Similarly, we can also represent 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 relations
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 Examples of binary relations: 
\begin_inset Formula $\in$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $=$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\le$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $>$
\end_inset

, parallel, congruent 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Example: 3 and 5 are in relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smaller".
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ternary relations: sum, difference, product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
——
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Family
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 relations: father, son, mother, husband, mother-in-law, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ldots$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
parents – ternary relation (
\begin_inset Formula $x,y,z$
\end_inset

 are in the relation if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are parents of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
——
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a meaningful binary relation for some mathematical theory 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal T}$
\end_inset

 with universal set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 will be presented with the set of exactly those ordered pairs of elements
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 whose first coordinate is in relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with the second coordinate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is in relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $R(x,y)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\{(x,y)~;~x,y\in S\inn xRy\}
\]

\end_inset

or simply (if the universal set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is clear from the context): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\{(x,y)~;~xRy\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-ary, we use 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-tuples: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\{(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n})~;~R(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n})\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
——
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A binary relation is therefore 
\series bold
a subset of the Cartesian product
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $S\times S=:S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-ary relation is a subset of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-fold Cartesian product of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with itself, 
\begin_inset Formula $S\times\cdots\times S=\Pi_{i=1}^{n}S=:S^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{1,2,3,4\}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Binary relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smaller
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $<(x,y)\cee x<y$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
<=\{(1,2),(1,3),(1,4),(2,3),(2,4),(3,4)\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ternary relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sum
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $+(x,y,z)\cee x+y=z$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
+=\{(1,1,2),(1,2,3),(1,3,4),(2,1,3),(2,2,4),(3,1,4)\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{1,2,3,4,5,6\}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

multiple
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R(x,y)\cee x$
\end_inset

 is a multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, that is,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists k)(k$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=k\cdot y$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\{(1,1),(2,1),(2,2),(3,1),(3,3),(4,1),(4,2),(4,4),(5,1),(5,5),(6,1),(6,2),(6,3),(6,6)\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ternary relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

product
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot(x,y,z)\cee z=x\cdot y$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cdot=\{(1,1,1),(1,2,2),(1,3,3),(1,4,4),(1,5,5),(1,6,6),(2,1,2),
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(2,2,4),(2,3,6),(3,1,3),(3,2,6),(4,1,4),(5,1,5),(6,1,6)\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Unary
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

prime
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P(x)\cee x$
\end_inset

 is a prime:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $P=\{2,3,5\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we represented relations with sets, we can also speak about relations
 
\begin_inset Formula $R\cup T$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R\cap T$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R\brez T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let us denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\leq}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{<}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{=}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\ge}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{>}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\neq}$
\end_inset

 respectively the relations 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smaller or equal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

smaller
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

greater or equal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

greater
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

non-equal
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (e.g., on the set of positive integers).
 Then: 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$$(x
\backslash
leq  y) = (x<y) 
\backslash
cup (x = y)$$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$$(x> y) = (x
\backslash
ge y) 
\backslash
brez (x = y)$$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$$(x> y) = (x
\backslash
ge y) 
\backslash
cap (x 
\backslash
neq y)$$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{\leq}=R_{<}\cup R_{=}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{>}=R_{\ge}\brez R_{=}=R_{\ge}\cap R_{\neq}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us now focus on 
\series bold
binary relations
\series default
 (these are of particular interest, as we shall see in the chapter on order
 structures).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a binary relation on a universal set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R=\{(x,y)~;~xRy\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all first coordinates of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is said to be the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 domain of relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all second coordinates of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is said to be the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 range (codomain) of relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Domain: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal D}R=\{x~;~(\exists y)(xRy)\}
\]

\end_inset

Range: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal R}R=\{y~;~(\exists x)(xRy)\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R=\{(1,2),(2,3),(2,4)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}R=\{1,2\}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal R}R=\{2,3,4\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
——
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Inverse relation:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{-1}=\{(y,x)~;~xRy\}
\]

\end_inset

Clearly: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $yR^{-1}x\cee xRy\,.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}R^{-1}={\cal R}R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal R}R^{-1}={\cal D}R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(R^{-1})^{-1}=R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\le}^{-1}~~=~~R_{\ge}\,,$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R_{<}^{-1}~~=~~R_{>}\,,$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R_{=}^{-1}~~=~~R_{=}\,,$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R_{\neq}^{-1}~~=~~R_{\neq}\,.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Composition of relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 be two binary relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T\circ R$
\end_inset

: composition of relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with relation 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xT\circ Ry\cee(\exists u)(xRu\inn uTy)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T\circ R=\{(x,y)~;~(\exists u)(xRu\inn uTy)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R=\{(1,3),(2,3)\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T=\{(3,1)\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T\circ R=\{(1,1),(2,1)\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ T=\{(3,3)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
brother 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 father 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

 father
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
father 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 brother 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

 uncle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(father 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 brother)
\begin_inset Formula $\cup$
\end_inset

(mother 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 brother) = uncle
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
sister 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 mother 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

 mother
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(wife 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 mother) 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup$
\end_inset

 (husband 
\begin_inset Formula $\circ$
\end_inset

 mother) = mother-in-law 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 In general 
\begin_inset Formula $T\circ R\neq R\circ T$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, associativity holds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V,T,R$
\end_inset

 be binary relations on universal set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
V\circ(T\circ R)=(V\circ T)\circ R\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\in V\circ(T\circ R)\cee xV\circ(T\circ R)y\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists u)(x(T\circ R)u\inn uVy)\cee(\exists u)(\exists v)(xRv\inn vTu\inn uVy)\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists v)(xRv\inn(\exists u)(vTu\inn uVy))\cee(\exists v)(xRv\inn v(V\circ T)y)\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x((V\circ T)\circ R)y\cee(x,y)\in(V\circ T)\circ R\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Inverse of a composition is equal to the composition of inverses in reverse
 order:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be binary relations on universal set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(T\circ R)^{-1}=R^{-1}\circ T^{-1}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\in(T\circ R)^{-1}\cee(y,x)\in T\circ R\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists u)(yRu\inn uTx)\cee(\exists u)(uR^{-1}y\inn xT^{-1}u)\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\exists u)(xT^{-1}u\inn uR^{-1}y)\cee x(R^{-1}\circ T^{-1})y\cee(x,y)\in R^{-1}\circ T^{-1}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the following relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R=\{(x,y)~;~x+y=a\}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $T=\{(x,y)~;~x+y=b\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $T\circ R=\{(x,y)~;~(\exists u)(x+u=a\inn u+y=b)\}=\{(x,y)~;~x-y=a-b\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ T=\{(x,y)~;~x-y=b-a\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}=R$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}=T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, equality in the above claim becomes 
\begin_inset Formula $(T\circ R)^{-1}=R\circ T\,.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Universal, null and identity relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 asmits three special relations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S\times S$
\end_inset

 – the universal relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset$
\end_inset

 – the null relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $I=\{(x,x)~;~x\in S\}$
\end_inset

 – the identity relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a binary relation on universal set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then 
\begin_inset Formula $I\circ R=R\circ I=R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $xI\circ Ry\cee(\exists u)(xRu\inn uIy)\cee xRy$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $xR\circ Iy\cee(\exists u)(xIu\inn uRy)\cee xRy$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 It also holds: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\emptyset\circ R=R\circ\emptyset=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(S\times S)\circ R=({\cal D}R)\times S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R\circ(S\times S)=S\times{\cal R}R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

