\begin_layout Subsection*
Equivalence relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equivalence
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is reflexive, symmetric and transitive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 the identity relation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is equivalence 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}R=S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}\circ R=R$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The condition is necessary:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $xRx\sledi{\cal D}R=S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xR^{-1}\circ Ry\sledi(\exists z)(xRz\inn zR^{-1}y)\sledi(\exists z)(xRz\inn yRz)\sledi(\exists z)(xRz\inn zRy)\sledi xRy\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xRy\sledi(xRy\inn yRy)\sledi(xRy\inn yR^{-1}y)\sledi xR^{-1}\circ Ry\,.
\]

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}\circ R=R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The condition is also sufficient:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}R=S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}\circ R=R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reflexivity: we need to show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(x\in S\sledi xRx)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}R=S$
\end_inset

, it follows 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in{\cal D}R\sledi(\exists y)(y\in S\inn xRy)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xRy\sledi xRy\inn yR^{-1}x\sledi xR^{-1}\circ Rx\sledi xRx\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Symmetry: we need to show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(\forall y)(x\in S\inn y\in S\inn xRy\sledi yRx)\,.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S\inn y\in S\inn xRy$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xRy\sledi(xRy\inn yRy)\sledi(yRy\inn yR^{-1}x)\sledi yR^{-1}\circ Rx\sledi yRx\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transitivity: we need to show 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(\forall y)(\forall z)(x\in S\inn y\in S\inn z\in S\inn xRy\inn yRz\sledi xRz).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S\inn y\in S\inn z\in S\inn xRy\inn yRz$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xRy\inn yRz\sledi xRy\inn zRy\sledi xRy\inn yR^{-1}z\sledi xR^{-1}\circ Rz\sledi xRz\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every equivalence relation has the nice property that it divides set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 on which it is defined into 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 non-empty and pairwise disjoint sets the union of which is exactly set
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Equivalence classes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be an equivalence relation defined on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equivalence class of element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with respect to the equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the set of all elements that are in relation with 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R[x]=\{y~;y\in S\inn yRx\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalence classes enjoy the following properties: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a reflexive relation, it holds 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $R[x]\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y\in R[x]\sledi R[y]=R[x]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Indeed: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $z\in R[y]\sledi zRy\inn yRx\sledi zRx\sledi z\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $z\in R[x]\sledi zRx\inn yRx\sledi zRx\inn xRy\sledi zRy\sledi z\in R[y]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $y\not\in R[x]\sledi R[x]\cap R[y]=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Indeed: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists z)(z\in R[x]\cap R[y])\sledi(\exists z)(R[z]=R[x]\inn R[z]=R[y])\sledi y\in R[y]=R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 Contradiction with assumption 
\begin_inset Formula $y\not\in R[x]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
It follows that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is in exactly one equivalence class.
 Namely in the one containing all elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 that are in relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 with it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every equivalence class is completely determined with an arbitrary element
 of it.
 We say that an arbitrary element of a class is a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 representative
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of the class.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The equivalence classes of a given equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 divide the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 into nonempty and pairwise disjoint sets the union of which is the set
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement htp
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename ekvivalencna.eps
	height 30mm

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such divisions are called partitions.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Partition of a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 = a set of nonempty and pairwise disjoint sets the union of which is 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, to every equivalence relation there corresponds a partition of set
 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The converse holds as well.
 Every partition 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 determines a unique equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that the sets in the partition are exactly the equivalence classes
 of relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are in relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 if and only if they belong to the same set of the partition: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xRy\cee(\exists X)(X\in{\cal A}\inn x\in X\inn y\in X)\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us verify that the so defined relation is an equivalence relation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
reflexivity: 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S\sledi(\exists X)(X\in{\cal A}\inn x\in X)\sledi xRx\,.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
symmetry: 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy\sledi(\exists X)(X\in{\cal A}\inn x\in X\inn y\in X)\sledi(\exists X)(X\in{\cal A}\inn y\in X\inn x\in X)\sledi yRx\,.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
transitivity: 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy\inn yRz\sledi(\exists X)(X\in{\cal A}\inn x\in X\inn y\in X)\inn(\exists Y)(Y\in{\cal A}\inn y\in Y\inn z\in Y)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is both in 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 Since the sets are pairwise disjoint, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $X=Y$
\end_inset

.
 But then 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 is also in set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $xRz$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
A question for thought:
\series default
 Justify that partition 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 coincides with the set of equivalence classes of relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% 14.
 predavanje, 2 uri, 29.
 11.
 2011
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To every set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 on which some equivalence relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is defined, we can associate some new set, the elements of which are the
 equivalence classes of relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Quotient set of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S/R=\{R[x]~;~x\in S\}=\{X~;~(\exists x)(x\in S\inn X=R[x])\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The notion of quotient set represents a mathematical formulation of the
 logical notion of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 abstraction
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

: By moving from a given set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to the quotient set, we ignore all differences between objects belonging
 to the same equivalence class! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
zgled
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\{(1,1),(1,3),(2,2),(3,1),(3,3)\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R[1]=R[3]=\{1,3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R[2]=\{2\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $S/R=\{R[1],R[2],R[3]\}=\{R[1],R[2]\}=\{\{1,3\},\{2\}\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we define a partition 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}=\{\{1,2\},\{3\}\}$
\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, then we can define a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R'$
\end_inset

 by the rule 
\begin_inset Formula $xR'y\cee(\exists X)(X\in{\cal A}\inn x\in X\inn y\in Y)$
\end_inset

.
 It holds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R'=\{(1,1),(1,2),(2,1),(2,2),(3,3)\}=R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S/R'=\{\{1,2\},\{3\}\}={\cal A}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
kz
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Examples of equivalence relations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Fractions.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
In the set of fractions 
\begin_inset Formula $a/b\,,$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 be arbitrary integers and 
\begin_inset Formula $b\neq0$
\end_inset

, the definition of equality of two fractions 
\begin_inset Formula $a/b=c/d\cee ad=bc$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation.
 Each equivalence class with respect to this relation collects together
 all pairwise equal fractions and then represents the corresponding 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 rational number
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The corresponding quotient set is the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 set of rational numbers
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Congruences.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
In the set of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 integers
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 the relation 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 congruence modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $m>0$
\end_inset

 is a positive integer, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\equiv b\pmod{m}\cee m\textrm{ divides }a-b\,,
\]

\end_inset

is an equivalence relation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, the equivalence classes are the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 residue classes modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Each equivalence class contains all those numbers that give the same remainder
 (residue) when divided by 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Obviously there are exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 of these classes.
 These classes are called 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 integers modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The quotient set is the set of integers modulo 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Parallelism of lines.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
In the set of 
