\begin_layout Subsection
Functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Function is a central notion of classical and modern mathematics.
 From 
\begin_inset Formula $18$
\end_inset

th century on, the notion of a function was becoming increasingly more precise
 and general.
 The definition of a function as we know it today was given by Cauchy and
 Riemann:
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 For two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 function from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a rule that assigns to every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 a unique element of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Notation: 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 To avoid any doubt what is meant with the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rule
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, we can define functions as special relations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 A binary relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 unique
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 if: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(x,y)\in R\inn(x,z)\in R\sledi y=z
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 function
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (also 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 mapping, map, transformation
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

) is a unique binary relation.
 We usually denote functions with letters 
\begin_inset Formula $f,g,h,\ldots$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, and write 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to B$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}f=A$
\end_inset

 and the following holds: 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\in f\sledi x\in A\inn y\in B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all functions from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=f(x)\cee(x,y)\in f\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=\{(x,y)~;~x\in A\inn y=f(x)\in B\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

: independent variable, original, argument
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $y(=f(x))$
\end_inset

: dependent variable, image of element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following notation is also in use:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x\mapsto f(x)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

",
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A\overset{f}{\to}B$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Examples of functions:
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{2,4,6\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{$
\end_inset

points at the surface of planet Earth
\begin_inset Formula $\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=$
\end_inset

 temperature in 
\begin_inset Formula $^{\circ}C$
\end_inset

 at point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 on December 2, 2012, at 6:00 local time 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{$
\end_inset

people living on Earth at a certain time 
\begin_inset Formula $T\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=$
\end_inset

 age (in seconds) of person 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(x,y)~;~x\in A\inn y=f(x)\}$
\end_inset

 is sometimes referred to as the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 graph of a function.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Depictions of functions.

\series default
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, the graph of a function can also be depicted as a set of points in the
 plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R},~~~f(x)=x^{2}\,.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

