\backslash
subseteq B
\backslash
}$$.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{2,4,6\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}f=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}(f)=\{2,4\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 In general 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}f\subseteq B$
\end_inset

.
 If equality holds, 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}f=B$
\end_inset

, then we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 surjective
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 function.
 In this case we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 onto
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $B=\{2,4,6\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

 is not surjective.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g:A\to B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\{(1,2),(2,6),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

, is surjective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 The definition of a function allows that several originals have the same
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

-image.
 In the extreme case, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 maps all elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 into the same element of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 Such a function is called a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 constant (function)
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The other extreme occurs when two different originals always have different
 images:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 injective
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall y)(y\in\textrm{Im}f\sledi(\exists!x)(x\in A\inn f(x)=y))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(\forall y)(f(x)=f(y)\sledi x=y)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

 is not injective.
 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\{(1,2),(2,6),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq A$
\end_inset

.
 We write: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(U)=\{y~;~y\in B\inn(\exists x)(x\in U\inn f(x)=y)\}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f(U)$
\end_inset

 – image of subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 under mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{2,3\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(U)=\{f(2),f(3)\}=\{4\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 Clearly: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f(A)=\textrm{Im}f$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq V\sledi f(U)\subseteq f(V)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The images behave in the following way with respect to unions and intersections:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f(U\cup V)=f(U)\cup f(V)$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f(U\cap V)\subseteq f(U)\cap f(V)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Homework:
\series default
 Prove the above properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Inverse relation, preimages
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Inverse relation:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}=\{(y,x)~;~f(x)=y\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is not necessarily a function!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}=\{(2,1),(4,2),(4,3)\}$
\end_inset

 - is not a function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Preimage
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of element 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(y)=\{x~;~x\in A\inn f(x)=y\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq B$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Preimage of 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (under mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(E)=\{x~;~x\in A\inn f(x)\in E\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(2)=\{1\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(4)=\{2,3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(\{2,4\})=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(\textrm{Im}f)=A$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 It also holds: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq F\sledi f^{-1}(E)\subseteq f^{-1}(F)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Preimages are in good relations with unions, intersections, and differences:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(E\cup F)=f^{-1}(E)\cup f^{-1}(F)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(E\cap F)=f^{-1}(E)\cap f^{-1}(F)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(E\brez F)=f^{-1}(E)\brez f^{-1}(F)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Proof of the property 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(E\cap F)=f^{-1}(E)\cap f^{-1}(F)$
\end_inset

:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in f^{-1}(E\cap F)\cee f(x)\in E\cap F\cee f(x)\in E\inn f(x)\in F\cee
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cee x\in f^{-1}(E)\inn x\in f^{-1}(F)\cee x\in f^{-1}(E)\cap f^{-1}(F)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Homework:
\series default
 Prove the other two properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Similarly we can check that: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq A$
\end_inset

, it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
U\subseteq f^{-1}(f(U))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $E\subseteq B$
\end_inset

, it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(f^{-1}(E))\subseteq E
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
————————————————————————————————————
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to B$
\end_inset

.
 When is the inverse relation 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 a function?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}f$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is injective.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%(Indeed: to have  da bo $f^{-1}$ funkcija, ne smeta obstajati dva razlièna
 urejena para v $f^{-1}$, ki bi imela isto prvo koordinato $
\backslash
cee$ ne smeta obstajati dva razlièna urejena para v $f$, ki bi imela isto
 drugo koordinato, tj.~$f$ je injektivna.)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, if 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is a function, then for every element 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in\textrm{Im}f$
\end_inset

 there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in{\cal D}f$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}(y)=x$
\end_inset

.
 It holds that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(y)=x\cee f(x)=y\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f^{-1}(f(x))=x
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(f^{-1}(y))=y\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A particularly interesting case is given if function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is not only injective, but also surjective.
 In this case, we say that function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 bijective
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is bijective, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}f=B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is a function from 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
bigskip
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
-----------------------------
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
bigskip
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Composition of functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\circ f=\{(x,z)~;~(\exists y)((x,y)\in f\inn(y,z)\in g)\}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
=\{(x,z)~;~(\exists y)(f(x)=y\inn g(y)=z)\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}f\cap{\cal D}g=\emptyset$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f=\emptyset\,.$
\end_inset

 This example is not particularly interesting, so we usually require: 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}f\subseteq{\cal D}g$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $A\overset{f}{\to}B\overset{g}{\to}C$
\end_inset

.
 Under this condition: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g\circ f=\{(x,z)~;~z=g(f(x))\}
\]

\end_inset

relation 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f$
\end_inset

 is also a function (from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula $(g\circ f)(x)=g(f(x))$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g=\{(2,3),(4,5)\}$
\end_inset

 (Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}g=\textrm{Im}f$
\end_inset

.) 
\begin_inset Formula $g\circ f=\{(1,3),(2,5),(3,5)\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Just like compositions of binary relations, compositions of functions also
 enjoy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Associativity:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\overset{f}{\to}B\overset{g}{\to}C\overset{h}{\to}D\,,
\]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h\circ(g\circ f)=(h\circ g)\circ f\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Restrictions and extensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When are two functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 the same?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
According to the definition of equality of sets, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g$
\end_inset

 only if they have the same ordered pairs as elements.
 This is true precisely when the following two conditions are satisfied:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}f={\cal D}g$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for every element 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 of this common domain, it holds 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=g(x)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two particular ways of modifying a given function are particularly important:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Restriction:
\series default
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A\to B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq A$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 restriction
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is the function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 that has set 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 as its domain and such that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U$
\end_inset

, it holds 
\begin_inset Formula $g(x)=f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Notation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g=f_{|U}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $U=\{1,2\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{|U}=\{(1,2),(2,4)\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 If function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is a restriction of function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 extension
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Canonical decomposition of a function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:A{\to}B$
\end_inset

.
 Let us define the following relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 on set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xRy\cee f(x)=f(y)\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an equivalence relation: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

 it holds 
\begin_inset Formula $xRx$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $xRy\sledi f(x)=f(y)\sledi f(y)=f(x)\sledi yRx$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $xRy\inn yRz\sledi f(x)=f(y)\inn f(y)=f(z)\sledi f(x)=f(z)\sledi xRz$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let us compute the quotient set 
\begin_inset Formula $A/R$
\end_inset

 (the set of all equivalence classes).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us first map set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 onto
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 set 
\begin_inset Formula $A/R$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p:A{\to}A/R
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(a)=R[a]
\]

\end_inset

Mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is surjective.
 It is called a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 natural mapping
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, let us define a mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 from the quotient set 
\begin_inset Formula $A/R$
\end_inset

 to set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 so that function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 will be the composition of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g\circ p$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g:A/R{\to}B
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(u)=f(x)\,,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary representative of equivalence class 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 (that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in u$
\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is well defined (the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $g(u)$
\end_inset

 is independent of the choice of representative of class 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\in u\inn y\in u\sledi xRy\sledi f(x)=f(y)\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is injective: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(u)=g(v)\inn g(u)=f(x)\inn g(v)=f(y)\sledi f(x)=f(y)\sledi xRy\sledi u=v\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It follows from the definitions of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $f=g\circ p$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

.
 Then: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(g\circ p)(x)=g(p(x))=g(R[x])=f(x)\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
We can decompose 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename dekompozicija.eps
	height 20mm

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Izpeljali smo naslednjo dekompozicijo funkcije $f:A{
\backslash
to} B$:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{center}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
includegraphics[height=20mm]{dekompozicija.eps}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{center}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Pri tem je:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
begin{itemize}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%  
\backslash
