\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%$xRy 
\backslash
cee f(x) = f(y)
\backslash
,.$
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%  
\backslash
item $g:A/R{
\backslash
to} B$ je injektivna preslikava, definirana s predpisom $g(u) = f(x)
\backslash
,,$ kjer je $x
\backslash
in u$.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
item $f = g
\backslash
circ p$.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
end{itemize}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

This decomposition can be further refined by introducing a mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, given by the same rule as 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

, but that maps to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}g=\textrm{Im}f$
\end_inset

.
 Mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is then bijective: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h:A/R{\to}\textrm{Im}f
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
h(u)=g(u)\,.
\]

\end_inset

Finally, we map set 
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}f$
\end_inset

 to set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 with the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 identity mapping
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

, which fixes all elements: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i:\textrm{Im}f{\to}B
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i(y)=y\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in A$
\end_inset

, it holds 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
i(h(p(x)))=h(p(x))=g(p(x))=f(x)\,.
\]

\end_inset

Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=i\circ h\circ p\,.
\]

\end_inset

This way, we obtain 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 canonical decomposition
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename dekompozicija2en.eps
	height 20mm

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,2,3\},B=\{2,4,6\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\{(1,2),(2,4),(3,4)\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(1)=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(2)=f(3)=4$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equivalence relation: 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\{(1,1),(2,2),(3,3),(2,3),(3,2)\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quotient set: 
\begin_inset Formula $A/R=\{\{1\},\{2,3\}\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\textrm{Im}f=\{2,4\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Natural mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $p(1)=\{1\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p(2)=p(3)=\{2,3\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $g:\{\{1\},\{2,3\}\}\to\{2,4,6\}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $g(\{1\})=f(1)=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\{2,3\})=f(2)=f(3)=4$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $h:\{\{1\},\{2,3\}\}\to\{2,4\}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\{1\})=g(\{1\})=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $h(\{2,3\})=g(\{2,3\})=4$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Identity mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $i:\{2,4\}\to\{2,4,6\}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $i(2)=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $i(4)=4$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename dekompozicija3en.eps
	height 20mm

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Order structures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Besides equivalence relations and functions, relations that generate a
 certain 
\shape italic
order
\shape default
 among the elements of a given set are of particular importance in mathematics.
 The order can be more or less strict, so we deal with different order structure
s.
 As we shall see, these structures form a hierarchy and are thus ordered
 on their own.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Let us start with the most general structures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a universal set and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 a relation on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We obtain the most general structure if we only require transitivity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is not a particularly interesting structure: the null relation, the
 identity relation and the universal relation are all transitive!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 virtually orders
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive and reflexive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

virtually
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 relates to our intuitive notion of order, since the universal relation
 
\begin_inset Formula $S\times S$
\end_inset

 is a virtual order on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, even though it does not order anything!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 partially orders
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive, reflexive and antisymmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a partial order on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then, a pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(S,R)$
\end_inset

 is called a partially ordered set or, shortly, a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 poset
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is smaller than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

"
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is greater than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example of a partial order:
\series default
 relation of set inclusion 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

", defined on an arbitrary family of subsets of a given universal set 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal U}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 might not be comparable with respect to relation of inclusion!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This holds also in general.
 This is where the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

partial order
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\series default
 relation of divisibility on the set of positive integers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is also a partial order.
 Two numbers might be incomparable with respect to this relation (e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $5$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

, or 
\begin_inset Formula $12$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $16$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 The relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\le$
\end_inset

"
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

on the set of real numbers also satisfies all conditions of a partial order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even more: this relation is also total, since every two real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $x\le y$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\le x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 totally
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 linearly orders
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive, reflexive, antisymmetric and total.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 However: 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is total 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi R$
\end_inset

 is reflexive!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(if in the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(\forall y)(xRy\ali yRx)$
\end_inset

 we take 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

, we get 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall x)(xRx)$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset

totally (linearly) orders
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive, antisymmetric and total.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
——————————————————————————
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% 16.
 predavanje, 2 uri, 7.
 12.
 2011
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Relations of strict inclusion 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\subset$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and strict inequality 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
they are both transitive and irreflexive 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
both are asymmetric 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
relation of strict inclusion determines only a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 partial
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 order (since there exist pairs of incomparable sets) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
on the other hand, relation of strict inequality stroge determines a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

total
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 order: it is 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 strict total
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, any two 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 different
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 real numbers are pairwise comparable with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every asymmetric relation is also irreflexive.
 Hence we can define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 strictly partially orders
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive and asymmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Analogously:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 strictly linearly orders
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive, asymmetric and strict total.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a strict partial order on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is below 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

"
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is smaller than 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

"
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is above 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

"
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

or
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(The same terminology is also used if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a partial order and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
——————————————————————————
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider one more relation of order: 
\series bold
preorder
\series default
 (or: quasiorder).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A model for preorder is for example the relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is at least as tall as
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the set of all people.
 It is transitive and total (therefore also reflexive).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But it is not antisymmetric! If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is at least as tall as
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is at least as tall as
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we can only infer that 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are equally tall, and not that 
\begin_inset Formula $x=y$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 preorder
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive and total.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
—————————————————————————— 
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have seen 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

 different order structures.
 Let us define on the set that contains as elements these 
\begin_inset Formula $7$
\end_inset

 structures, relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is a special case of
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a special case of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 if every relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{x}$
\end_inset

 that determines structure 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 also has all the properties of structure 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
linear order is a special case of partial order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
strict linear order is a special case of strict partial order 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

is a special case of
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is transitive, reflexive and antisymmetric, hence it determines a partial
 order among these structures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Partial orders can be represented with so called
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Hasse diagrams:
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename strukture-en.eps
	height 50mm

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hasse diagram
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 - relation that partially or strictly partially orders 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $xRy\cee$
\end_inset

 we can get from 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in the diagram moving only upwards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 ——————————————————————————
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{1,2,3\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $S={\cal P}(A)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

: strict inclusion 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
