\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 We may require the existence of infimum and supremum for 
\shape italic
all
\shape default
 nonempty subsets (not only for finite ones):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has the structure of a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 complete lattice
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 partially orders set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
underline{every}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 nonempty subset 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-inf and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-sup.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Clearly, every complete lattice is also a lattice with respect to the same
 relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Every finite lattice is a complete lattice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 – arbitrary set
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(A)$
\end_inset

 is a complete lattice for 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty family of subsets of set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\subseteq)\textrm{-}\inf{\cal A}=\cap{\cal A}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\subseteq)\textrm{-}\sup{\cal A}=\cup{\cal A}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Question:
\series default
 Is the set 
\begin_inset Formula ${\mathbb{R}}$
\end_inset

 of real numbers a complete lattice with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\le$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is not a complete lattice with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\le$
\end_inset

: the whole set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is not bounded! (it has neither a supremum nor an infimum)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can extend the set of real numbers to a complete lattice by adding to
 it elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty$
\end_inset

, and require 
\begin_inset Formula $x\le\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty\le x$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

