\begin_layout Subsection*
Well ordering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just like the set of real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, the set of natural numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

 is also strictly linearly oredered with relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But it also has the following additional property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Every nonempty subset of natural numbers has a smallest element!
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the set of all natural numbers such an element is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the set of all prime numbers the smallest element is 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of real numbers does not have this property! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 does not have any smallest element 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x~;~x\in\mathbb{R}\inn x>0\}$
\end_inset

 also not 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 The property that every nonempty subset has a smallest element is referred
 to 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 well ordering
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 – relation on set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (typically partial or strict partial order) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $a\in S$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
