\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 minimal element
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal element
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall y)(y\in S\inn y\neq a\sledi\neg(yRa))$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $b\in S$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 least element
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 (or 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least element
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall y)(y\in S\inn y\neq b\sledi bRy)$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is below 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

"
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 No element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is below a minimal element.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A least element is below every other element.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Every element that is incomparable with every other element is a minimal
 element.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\series bold
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Partial orders 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 are given with the following Hasse diagrams: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Hasse2-en.eps
	height 40mm

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be antisymmetric.
 Then every 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least element is also 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 By contradiction.
 Suppose that there exists an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least element 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 that is not 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is not 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\neg(\forall y)(y\in S\inn y\neq b\sledi\neg(yRb))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi(\exists y)(y\in S\inn y\neq b\inn yRb)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least, it holds 
\begin_inset Formula $bRy$
\end_inset

.
 But since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is antisymmetric, from 
\begin_inset Formula $bRy\inn yRb$
\end_inset

 it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $y=b$
\end_inset

.
 This is in contradiction with 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq b$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $R\textrm{ {\em well orders }}S\cee R\textrm{ is strict total, irreflexive and }$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $(\forall X)(X\subseteq S\inn X\neq\emptyset\sledi X\textrm{ has an \ensuremath{R}-minimal element})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 well orders 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a strict linear order of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 We need to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive, asymmetric and strict total.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Strict totality follows from the definition of a well order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Asymmetry: Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yRx$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is irreflexive, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq x$
\end_inset

.
 But then, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y\}$
\end_inset

 does not have any 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal element: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $xRy\sledi y$
\end_inset

 is not 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $yRx\sledi x$
\end_inset

 is not 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is asymmetric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transitivity can be shown similarly: Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
xRy\inn yRz\inn\neg(xRz)\,.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is irreflexive, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq z$
\end_inset

.
 Since it is strict total, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $zRx$
\end_inset

 and consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $z\neq x$
\end_inset

.
 The set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y,z\}$
\end_inset

 has an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal element, however: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
this element is not 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy\inn x\neq y$
\end_inset

, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
this element is not 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $yRz\inn y\neq z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
this element is not 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $zRx\inn z\neq x$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This contradiction shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is transitive.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a well ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then every 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal element is also 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal for 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi(\forall y)(y\in S\inn y\neq x\sledi\neg(yRx))$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Strict totality: 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq x\inn\neg(yRx)\sledi xRy$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently: 
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall y)(y\in S\inn y\neq x\sledi xRy)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least element.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a well ordering on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

 it holds: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x\textrm{ is }R\textrm{-least }\cee x\textrm{ is }R\textrm{-minimal}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{cor}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a well ordering on a nonempty set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 a unique
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least (or 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-minimal) element.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Suppose that there exist two different 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least elements 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $xRy$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $yRx$
\end_inset

.
 But this is a contradiction with asymmetry.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 One can also define well ordering by means of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least elements, but then we also need to require asymmetry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 well orders 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is strict total, asymmetric and the following condition holds:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $(\forall X)(X\subseteq S\inn X\neq\emptyset\sledi X$
\end_inset

 has an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least element).
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{prop}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\series bold
Homework.

\series default
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{proof}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Remark:
\series default
 The notion of well ordering is important because it generalizes the ordering
 
\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

 on the set of natural numbers.
 The principle of induction can also be generalized to well ordered sets
 (this is the so called
