\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Immediate successor.
 Greatest element.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the set of natural numbers, ordered with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $<$
\end_inset

", every number has its (uniquely determined) immediate successor.
 What characterizes an immediate successor 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 of a number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $x<y$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
for every other number 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x<z$
\end_inset

, it also holds 
\begin_inset Formula $y<z$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a well ordering on a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Element 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

