\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

: sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}\times A_{2}=\{(x,y)~;~x\in A_{1},~y\in A_{2}\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every ordered pair is determined so that the first element is chosen from
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

, and the second one from 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Such a choice corresponds to a function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f:\{1,2\}\to A_{1}\cup A_{2}
\]

\end_inset

such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(1)\in A_{1}\textrm{ and }f(2)\in A_{2}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{1}\times A_{2}=\{f:\{1,2\}\to A_{1}\cup A_{2},f(1)\in A_{1},f(2)\in A_{2}\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can write a similar expression for Cartesian products of finitely many
 factors: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{1}\times\cdots\times A_{n}=\{f:\{1,\ldots,n\}\to A_{1}\cup\cdots\cup A_{n},f(1)\in A_{1},\ldots,f(n)\in A_{n}\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 This way, we can generalize the definition of the Cartesian product to
 products of an arbitrary set family:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal A}=\{A_{\lambda}~;~\lambda\in I\}
\]

\end_inset

be an arbitrary (nonempty) set family.
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Cartesian product
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\prod{\cal A}=\prod_{\lambda\in I}A_{\lambda}=\{f:I\to\cup_{\lambda\in I}A_{\lambda},~(\forall\lambda)(\lambda\in I\sledi f(\lambda)\in A_{\lambda})\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An element 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\prod_{\lambda\in I}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is called a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 choice function
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If at least one of the sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is empty, then also the product 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod_{\lambda\in I}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 is empty (since if 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

 then the condition 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\lambda)\in A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 can certainly not be satisfied)! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $(\exists\lambda)(\lambda\in I\inn A_{\lambda}=\emptyset)\sledi\prod_{\lambda\in I}A_{\lambda}=\emptyset$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the finite case also the converse holds: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(\forall\lambda)(\lambda\in I\sledi A_{\lambda}\neq\emptyset)\sledi\prod_{\lambda\in I}A_{\lambda}\neq\emptyset\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 What about the infinite case??
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}\neq\emptyset$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in I$
\end_inset

 then there exists at least one choice function."
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Can we prove this?
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cohen (1963): this proposition is unprovable from the remaining axioms of
 Set Theory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
The Cartesian product axiom:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary family of nonempty sets, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\prod{\cal A}$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
The Axiom of Choice (AC):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}=\{A_{\lambda}~;~\lambda\in I\}$
\end_inset

 is an arbitrary family of nonempty sets, then there exists at least one
 funcion 
\begin_inset Formula $f:I\to\cup_{\lambda\in I}A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\lambda)\in A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zermelo, 1904 – used AC when proving the Well ordering theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Zermelo Axiom)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% 19.
 predavanje, 2 uri, 20.
 12.
 2011
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Gödel's Theorem (1940):
\series default
 The Axiom of Choice is consistent with the remaining axioms of Set Theory:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Together with the consistency of the Axiom of Choice, Kurt Gödel also demonstrat
ed the consistency of the continuum hypothesis with the other axioms of
 Set Theory.
 This way he solved the first of its famous 
\begin_inset Formula $23$
\end_inset

 problems, that German mathematician David Hilbert posed to the mathematical
 community in 
\begin_inset Formula $1900$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\shape italic
If we can derive a contradiction in a system, where, besides other axioms
 we also assume the Axiom of Choice, then a contradiction can also be derived
 in the system that only relies on the remaining axioms and has no Axiom
 of Choice.

\shape default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the Axiom of Choice one can prove many important theorems in various
 areas of mathematics (algebra, analysis, topology, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ldots$
\end_inset

), as well as some less intuitive theorems, e.g.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

 the 
\series bold
Banach–Tarski paradox:
\series default
 A three-dimensional unit ball can be the cut into finitely many pairwise
 disjoint parts such that translations and rotations of them can be composed
 into 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 two
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 identical copies of the original ball!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 The Axiom of Choice is equivalent to many other propositions, for example
 to the following two: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Every binary relation contains a function with the same domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 is a family of pairwise disjoint nonempty sets, then there exists a set
 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 such that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in{\cal A}$
\end_inset

, set 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cap A$
\end_inset

 contains exactly one element.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Maximality principles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will give four maximality principles and show that they are logically
 equivalent.
 They are also equivalent to the Axiom of Choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, two definitions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 be a partial order on 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 contains an element 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 such that for every other element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 it does not hold
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $mRx$
\end_inset

, then we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-maximal element
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

