Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following partial order has two maximal elements.
 The circled elements form a chain: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename verige-en.eps
	height 50mm

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
1.
 Hausdorff maximality principle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a set partially ordered with relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal V}$
\end_inset

 be the family of all chains: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal V}=\{X\subseteq S~;~X\textrm{ is a chain}\}\,.
\]

\end_inset

The set 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal V}$
\end_inset

 is partially ordered with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When is 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 a maximal element of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal V}$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When for every other 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\in{\cal V}$
\end_inset

 it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is not a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $X\nsubseteq Y$
\end_inset

.
 Such an element is called a 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 maximal chain
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
underline{Hausdorff maximality principle:}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Set 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal V}$
\end_inset

 has at least one maximal element with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every poset has a maximal chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
2.
 Zorn's lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zorn's lemma says that the condition that every chain in a poset is bounded
 from above is a sufficient condition for the existence of a maximal element
 in the given poset.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
underline{Zorn's lemma:}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a set partially ordered with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and suppose that every chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-upper bound.
 Then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-maximal element.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
3.
 Tukey's maximality principle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary set and let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary (nonempty) family of subsets of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 (hence 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}\subseteq{\cal P}(S)$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 of finite character
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 an arbitrary subset 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq S$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 if and only if every 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 finite
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 subset of set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
bigskip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%{
\backslash
small {
\backslash
bf Example:} druina vseh linearno neodvisnih mnoic danega vektorskega
 prostora.}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
underline{Tukey's maximality principle:}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 is of finite character, then 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 has at least one maximal element with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

" (which partially orders 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
4.
 Kuratowski's lemma.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a set partially ordered with relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V\subseteq S$
\end_inset

 be a chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
{\cal U}_{V}=\{X\subseteq S~;~X\textrm{ is a chain in }S\textrm{ and }V\subseteq X\}\,.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula ${\cal U}_{V}$
\end_inset

 is partially ordered with relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
underline{Kuratowski's lemma:}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal U}_{V}$
\end_inset

 has at least one maximal element with respect to inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 Every chain is contained in a maximal chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
————————————————————
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All these maximality principles are pairwise logically equivalent.
 We will show:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textrm{(Hausdorff) \ensuremath{\sledi} (Zorn) \ensuremath{\sledi} (Tukey) \ensuremath{\sledi} (Kuratowski) \ensuremath{\sledi} (Hausdorff)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% 20.
 predavanje, 2 uri, 21.
 12.
 2011, poprava kviza 15'
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Step 1: (Hausdorff) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (Zorn)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 partially order 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and let every chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 have 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-upper bound.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Hausdorff, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 contains at least one maximal chain 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The hypothesis of Zorn's lemma says that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 has an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-upper bound 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We claim that 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-maximal element.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose this is not the case.
 Then there exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $uRx$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound for chain 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $yRu$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $uRx$
\end_inset

 and therefore, by transitivity, 
\begin_inset Formula $yRx$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently 
\begin_inset Formula $y\neq x$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $y=x$
\end_inset

 would imply 
\begin_inset Formula $uRx$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $xRu$
\end_inset

 and also 
\begin_inset Formula $x=u$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore the chain 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a proper subset of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cup\{x\}$
\end_inset

.
 But the set 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cup\{x\}$
\end_inset

 is linearly ordered with relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, hence it is a chain.
 This is in contradiction with the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a maximal chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We thus showed that set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 has an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-maximal element.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Step 2: (Zorn) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (Tukey)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 be a nonempty family of subsets of a given set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 be of finite character.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 is partially ordered with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us check that every chain in this family has an upper bound!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary chain in family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of set 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 are subsets of set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, which are linearly ordered with relation 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is a chain).
 Let us take the union of all the elements of this chain, 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\cup V$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is an upper bound for 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 (for every element 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in V$
\end_inset

 it holds 
\begin_inset Formula $X\subseteq\cup V=W$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us show that 
\begin_inset Formula $W\in{\cal D}$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 is of finite character, it suffice to show that every finite subset of
 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\{a_{1},\ldots,a_{n}\}\subseteq W$
\end_inset

.
 There exist sets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1},\ldots,A_{n}\in V$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}\in A_{i}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 But since these sets are linearly ordered, one of these 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 sets, say 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}$
\end_inset

, contains all others.
 It follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}$
\end_inset

 also contains 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subseteq A_{j}\in V$
\end_inset

 and therefore also 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{j}\in{\cal D}$
\end_inset

, it follows that also 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in{\cal D}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is a finite subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, which is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

, and family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 is of finite character.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have showed that every chain has an upper bound with respect to relation
 of inclusion.
 It follows from Zorn's lemma that family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 has at least one maximal element.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Step 3: (Tukey) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (Kuratowski)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 partially order set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 be the family of all the subsets 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cup V$
\end_inset

 is a chain in set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us verify that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 is of finite character!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in{\cal D}$
\end_inset

.
 Then also every finite subset 
\begin_inset Formula $X'$
\end_inset

 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is in 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

: namely, 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cup X$
\end_inset

 is a chain, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $V\cup X'$
\end_inset

 is also a chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And conversely: let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a subset of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 contains all finite subsets of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 This means that for every two elements 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y\in X$
\end_inset

 it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{x,y\}\cup V$
\end_inset

 is a chain.
 It is evident that then also the set 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cup V$
\end_inset

 is a chain.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in{\cal D}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By Tukey, set 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

 contains a maximal element 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 with respect to relation of inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the definition of family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}$
\end_inset

, the set 
\begin_inset Formula $M\cup V$
\end_inset

 is a maximal chain in set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 containing chain 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 But this is exactly the statement of Kuratowski's lemma.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Step 4: (Kuratowski) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (Hausdorff)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 partially order a set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the empty set.
 This is certainly a chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

; the condition about linear ordering of its elements is vacuously satisfied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But the empty set is a subset of every chain in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 According to Kuratowski's lemma, a maximal chain exists and at the same
 time is also a maximal element of the family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal V}$
\end_inset

 of all chains with respect to relation of inclusion 
\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

.
 But this is precisely the content of Hausdorff maximality principle.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

% 21.
 predavanje, 2 uri, 3.
 1.
 2012
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Ponovitev:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Spoznali smo tiri principi maksimalnosti and pokazali, da so med seboj
 ekvivalentni:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
