\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Maximality principles are also equivalent to the axiom of choice:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Tukey) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (axiom of choice) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (Hausdorff)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
(Tukey) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (axiom of choice)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}=\{A_{\lambda}~;~\lambda\in I\}$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary family of nonempty sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

 be the set of all functions the domain 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}f$
\end_inset

 of which is a subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 and that assign to each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in{\cal D}f$
\end_inset

 an element 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\lambda)\in A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every such function is a set of ordered pairs, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\subseteq I\times\cup{\cal A}\,.
\]

\end_inset

Set 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

 is a family of subsets of the Cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $I\times\cup{\cal A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
Claim: 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

 is of finite character.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proof of claim: Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in{\cal F}$
\end_inset

.
 Clearly, every finite subset of function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, take an arbitrary subset 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 of the Cartesian product 
\begin_inset Formula $I\times\cup{\cal A}$
\end_inset

 with the property that every finite subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this case, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is also a function and an element of family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, if in the set 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 there existed two different pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,a)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,b)$
\end_inset

 with the same first coordinate, then the two-element subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\lambda,a),(\lambda,b)\}$
\end_inset

 would not be a function, which is in contradiction with the assumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similarly we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $g\in{\cal F}$
\end_inset

, since for every 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,a)\in g$
\end_inset

, it holds that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{(\lambda,a)\}\in{\cal F}$
\end_inset

, therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We proved that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

 is of finite character.
 Tukey's maximality principle implies that 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

 has at least one maximal element 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 with respect to relation 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\subseteq$
\end_inset

".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us verify that this 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a choice function!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since 
\begin_inset Formula $F\in{\cal F}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a function.
 Hence, it is enough to show that the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose this is not the case.
 Then, there exists an index 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in I\backslash{\cal D}f$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary element of the non-empty set 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 and let us make the ordered pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda,a)$
\end_inset

 and the union 
\begin_inset Formula $F\cup\{(\lambda,a)\}$
\end_inset

.
 This union is an element of family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

 that contains function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 as a proper subset.
 This, however, is in contradiction with the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a maximal element of family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal F}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal D}F=I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is indeed a choice function.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is possible to show that 
\series bold
(axiom of choice) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (Hausdorff)
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
See 
\shape italic
Niko Prijatelj: Matematične strukture I, p.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

135–142
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the proof of implication 
\series bold
(axiom of choice) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (Zorn's lemma)
\series default
, see 
\shape italic
Paul Halmos: Naive Set Theory, p.
 63–65
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Well ordering theorem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\shape italic
Perhaps the deepest reason why the axiom of choice seems problemtic to many
 mathematicians stems from the fact that the axiom of choice implies the
 well ordering theorem, that states that every set can be well ordered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%
\backslash
bigskip
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

%Aksiom izbire je logièno ekvivalenten tudi t.i.~thmu o dobri ureditvi.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 
\series bold
Well ordering theorem
\series default
: For every set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 there exists a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that well orders
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Well ordering theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $\cee$
\end_inset

 axiom of choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 Let us show the easier of both implications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Well ordering theorem 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 axiom of choice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}=\{A_{\lambda}~;~\lambda\in I\}$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary family of nonempty sets.
 According to the well ordering theorem, there exists a relation 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that well orders 
\shape italic
the union of family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset


\shape default
, 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup{\cal A}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since every subset 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 of family 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal A}$
\end_inset

 is a nonempty subset of the union 
\begin_inset Formula $\cup{\cal A}$
\end_inset

, it has an 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least element.
 Hence, we can define the choice function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 by assigning to each element 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\in I$
\end_inset

 the 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

-least element of set 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(\lambda)=R\textrm{-least element in }A_{\lambda}\,.
\]

\end_inset

The axiom of choice is thus verified.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
qed
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also possible to show the implication 
\series bold
(axiom of choice) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (well-ordering theorem)
\series default
.
 See 
\shape italic
Niko Prijatelj: Matematične strukture I, p.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

143–151
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a proof of implication of 
\series bold
(Zorn's lemma) 
\begin_inset Formula $\sledi$
\end_inset

 (well-ordering theorem)
\series default
 see 
\shape italic
Paul Halmos: Naive Set Theory, p.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

68
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equipollent sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When do two finite sets have the same number of elements?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We remove one element from each of the sets and repeat the procedure.
 The two sets have the same number of elements if and only if they become
 empty simultaneously with the above procedure.
 This way, we found a bijective mapping between the two sets.
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

 In general:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
em
\end_layout

\end_inset

 equipollent
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 to a set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 if there exists at least one bijective mapping from 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\sim B\,.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also say that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 
\shape italic
have the same cardinality
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $----------------------------------$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{N}=\{0,1,2,\ldots\}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $2\mathbb{N}=\{0,2,4,\ldots\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $f:2\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(2n)=2n$
\end_inset

 is not a bijective mapping
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $g:2\mathbb{N}\to\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $g(2n)=n$
\end_inset

 is a bijective mapping! Hence the sets are equipollent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $----------------------------------$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a set.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 be the set of all functions of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $f:X\to\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)\sim{\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Indeed: Consider the mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $F:C(X)\to{\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

 defined with the rule 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F(f)=f^{-1}(1)=\{x\in X\,:\,f(x)=1\}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C(X)$
\end_inset

.
 Mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 is a bijective mapping from the set 
\begin_inset Formula $C(X)$
\end_inset

 onto the set 
\begin_inset Formula ${\cal P}(X)$
\end_inset

.
 There are several ways to verify this, for example by finding a mapping
 
\begin_inset Formula $G:{\cal P}(X)\to C(X)$
\end_inset

 that is inverse to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, that is, that 
\begin_inset Formula $F\circ G=\textrm{id}_{{\cal P}(X)}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G\circ F=\textrm{id}_{C(X)}$
\end_inset

.
 Function 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 with these properties can be defined with the rule 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G(S)=\chi_{S}
\]

\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $S\subseteq X$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula ${\chi_{S}}:X\to\{0,1\}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
characteristic function
\series default
 of set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\chi_{S}(x)=
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

